URL reference: https://medium.com/learnings-from-the-paas/the-karpenter-effect-redefining-our-kubernetes-operations-80c7ba90a599
DateReviewed: 2025-07-16
Description: Our article today dives into the real-world use of the Karpenter tool. For that, we join Adevinta, and as background they tell us they are running 30 clusters with over 2K Kubernetes nodes which they need to manage. Here, they outline why they are using Karpenter to help out in this. They explain that in the past, K8s upgrades was a burdensome process, especially with things like the provider running out of instances of a certain type, which is out of your control. They used capacity reservations to ensure availability, a strange constraint. Now with Karpenter, they only have to worry about the control plane which is much smaller and takes less then a half hour to roll out, with worker nodes getting marked as "drifted" now that the AMI has been updated. They also mention that Karpneter will respect the config of Pod disruption budgets, allowing you to specify how much infra you can upgrade at once. What I like is they dig deep here, and even get into the YAML and talk about timings, so you get all the dirt. They also talk a bit about instance type flexibility, needed if there are constraints on a type you use in your AZ. With Karpenter, you can specify requirements which it can match to a few types. The article does more deep dives into Workload requirements, for things like GPU jobs or logging; and talk about the ability to get security updates in an automatic way. They also cover things like PDP, latency, and trying to get the "cheapest first". A very interesting piece.
BottomLine: Good longer piece on using Karpenter in large scale Kubernetes clusters
