URL reference: https://www.tenable.com/blog/3-quick-ways-to-improve-kubernetes-security
DateReviewed: 2025-07-18
Description: The article we'll be looking at focuses on 3 quick ways to improve Kubernetes security. We start with some background, referencing a report that notes lots of things open in various K8s hosts. They also note their recommendations are aimed at GCP. Their first recommendation is removing wide inbound access to cluster APIs - restricting the control plane access. They explain why, and also explain how to do this in GCP. Next is removing priv perms from containers - which restricts things like access to host devices and kernel parameters. They fill a bit of background and show how to do this too. Finally, they say to remove priv perms from publicly accessible groups. This is important, as you can allow people who are autheticate to *Google* access to your cluster, not just people known to your specific cluster. They advocate the removal of role-bindings from public groups. Interesting and quick security tune-up.
BottomLine: Quick and insightful tips that are aimed at GCP but do apply to Kubernetes more widely
